\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Volume sampling pipeline for generating per-bead training data. (1) The physical system is a tapered chain of 16 beads connected by spring rod elements. (2) Each sample is a random scenario: one bead with left and right neighbors sampled in polar coordinates around rest length. (3) Forces on the central bead are computed analytically. (4) Symplectic Euler advances velocity then position. (5) Input and target arrays are packed. (6) Volume sampling fills the reachable state space uniformly, unlike trajectory data which traces thin paths.}}{4}{figure.caption.1}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig:pipeline}{{1}{4}{Volume sampling pipeline for generating per-bead training data. (1) The physical system is a tapered chain of 16 beads connected by spring rod elements. (2) Each sample is a random scenario: one bead with left and right neighbors sampled in polar coordinates around rest length. (3) Forces on the central bead are computed analytically. (4) Symplectic Euler advances velocity then position. (5) Input and target arrays are packed. (6) Volume sampling fills the reachable state space uniformly, unlike trajectory data which traces thin paths}{figure.caption.1}{}}
